Under the terms of the Habitats Directive (Council of European Communities 1992) the UK is required to report at intervals on the condition of its marine Special Areas of Conservation (SAC).  This survey was designed to repeat previous work carried out by the Natural History Museum (NHM) in order to provide information on the condition of the SAC. Data for the survey was gathered using divers moving along a transect line making video recordings fo the biotopes. The dataset includes GIS biotope polygon data of the Thanet coast and a comparrison with previous data found in 1997 and 2004 by the NHM.</gco:CharacterString>    </gmd:abstract>    <!-- Originator Museum in 1997 (Tittley et al. 1998) used Phase II methods, diving at selected spots along 5 transects which stretched from ELWS to the boundary of the cSAC. These sites were relocated from the original data using a combination of GPS coordinates and depth. At each site, a shot line was dropped on the approximate location. A pair of divers then carried out a Phase II survey in the vicinity of the shot line, using the standard MNCR approach and recording the species present using the SACFOR semi-quantitative abundance scale (Hiscock 1996).  Each site was assigned a biotope according to the 97.06 version of the National Marine Biotope Classification (Connor et al. 1997).  Samples were collected of organisms that could not be identified in situ, most of them were identified in the field laboratory.
